                "text": "**Zero chart code.** No library, no drawing routine.",
                "style": "info"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "value": "Graphing lives once, at the AI layer — shared by everything.",
                "dim": true
              }
            ],
            "ratio": 50
          },
          "right": {
            "title": "At runtime",
            "accentColor": "primary",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "bullets",
                "items": [
                  "Read: the accounting API",
                  "Draw: the shared chart presenter",
                  "This pipeline appears in no source file"
                ]
              }
            ],
            "ratio": 50
          }
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "So every application settles into four slim parts. The shape of its data. Its rules. A basic view of its records. And whatever custom interfaces the model generates when you ask. Everything else — the charts, the dashboards, the exports — lives in a shared layer that no application owns.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "grid",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The slim application"
          },
          "title": "Four parts. Nothing more.",
          "gridColumns": 2,
          "items": [
            {
              "title": "Database schema",
              "description": "the shape of the data",
              "icon": "🧬",
              "accentColor": "primary"
            },
            {
              "title": "Business logic",
              "description": "rules that never guess",
              "icon": "⚖️",
              "accentColor": "info"
            },
            {
              "title": "Basic UI",
              "description": "the canonical views",
              "icon": "🪟",
              "accentColor": "accent"
            },
            {
              "title": "Generated UI",
              "description": "made by the model, on request",
              "icon": "✨",
              "accentColor": "highlight"
            }
          ],
          "footer": "Everything else lives in a shared layer no app owns."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Others see pieces of this. Satya Nadella predicts that business apps will, probably, all collapse — the logic moves to agents. The closest published cousin, agent native architecture, gives the agent equal access: it can operate every action the developers defined. But it cannot define one. That's the difference here. Maria's tracker had no developer. The schema itself was authored — for her.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "grid",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The discourse"
          },
          "title": "Access is not authorship",
          "gridColumns": 3,
          "items": [
            {
              "title": "Nadella",
              "description": "Business apps “probably” collapse — logic moves to agents",
              "accentColor": "primary",
              "icon": "🏢"
            },
            {
              "title": "Agent-native",
              "description": "The agent gets equal access — to developer-authored actions",
              "accentColor": "info",
              "icon": "🤝"
            },
            {
              "title": "This series",
              "description": "The agent authors the schema itself — per user",
              "accentColor": "highlight",
              "icon": "🖊️"
            }
          ],
          "footer": "Maria's tracker had no developer."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "Now the honest part. A generated app comes from a system that is sometimes confidently wrong, for a user who can't read a schema. So the invariants must hold. The host validates everything the model authors — an invalid app never runs. That was part three's harness. Keep the declarative layer small: extend it only where it beats the agent. And know where this earns its keep — accounting, contracts, places where the rules are the value. For notes? The model just edits the files.",
      "image": {
        "type": "slide",
        "slide": {
          "layout": "manifesto",
          "eyebrow": {
            "label": "The case against this",
            "color": "danger"
          },
          "title": "Who checks the work?",
          "items": [
            {
              "title": "The host validates",
              "description": "Every schema the model authors is checked first. An invalid app never runs. (Part 3's harness.)",
              "accentColor": "danger"
            },
            {
              "title": "Declare less",
              "description": "Extend the declarative layer only when it outperforms the agent.",
              "accentColor": "warning"
            },
            {
              "title": "Know the tiers",
              "description": "Real code where rules are the value: accounting, contracts. For notes, the plugin layer disappears.",
              "accentColor": "info"
            }
          ],
          "columns": 3,
          "footer": "Structure is checkable. Meaning is Part 5's problem."
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "text": "This was part four of six — and the short version. The full essay has the counterarguments, the file layouts, and the real accounting app that puts this to the test. Next, part five: what happens to the price of software, when the audience is one person.",
